## Plan

**Approach:** Build `scripts/dogfood-completeness-audit.sh` — a read-only bash
audit that reports, with bead/run/ref ids, the dogfood artifacts missing from a
bounded window of recent closed work and **exits non-zero on any gap**. It is
designed as a reusable, scriptable MECHANISM (not a one-off report): it builds
etude fresh, takes a `--bead <id>` single-bead mode so `etude-8hq.1` can call it
per-close, and a windowed batch mode (`--last N` / `--since <date>`) for a
sweep. This bead delivers ONLY the audit + its tests + docs; `etude-8hq.1`
(separate bead, blocked-by this one) wires it into close/push. 1 bead = 1 commit.

### Home decision (justify)
A **bash script alongside the other dogfood scripts**, not an `etude` subcommand
or a make target.
- It spans `bd` (closed beads + labels), `git` (refs / for-each-ref / ls-remote),
  the built `etude` binary (`run show`, manifest gates), and `make` (docs
  checks). Etude CORE must never know about beads/`bd` (the home/style precedent
  set by `dogfood-capture.sh`, `dogfood-gate-capture.sh`, `backfill-gate-records.sh`,
  `docs-reality-check.sh`), so this is project tooling, not a product command —
  no new etude command, no docs/cli blast radius (defect-class #6: blast radius
  is NONE).
- It builds etude fresh from source first (`go build -o "$bin" ./cmd/etude`),
  exactly like the four existing dogfood scripts, so it never inspects via a
  stale ambient binary.
- Closest precedent is `scripts/docs-reality-check.sh`: collect findings into an
  array, print a per-finding report to stderr, `exit 1` on any finding, `exit 0`
  with an OK summary otherwise. Mirror that contract.

### CLI
```
scripts/dogfood-completeness-audit.sh [--bead <id>] [--last <N>] [--since <date>]
                                      [--quiet] [--json]
```
- `--bead <id>`: audit exactly one closed bead (the close-time mode 8hq.1 calls).
- `--last <N>`: audit the N most-recently-closed in-scope beads (default N=9 ≈
  three cadence cohorts).
- `--since <date>`: audit in-scope beads closed on/after an ISO date.
- `--last`/`--since` are mutually exclusive; `--bead` overrides both.
- `--quiet`: suppress the per-check PASS lines; still print the final summary + all gaps.
- `--json`: emit a machine-readable `{checks:[...], gaps:[...], exit:N}` for the
  8hq.1 gate (text by default).

### Scoping rule — THE crux (precise + auditable)
Not every closed bead has or needs a run+gates. 24 of 50 currently-closed beads
have NO run ref — all pre-dogfood-habit infra/process beads (go-cli-scaffold,
phase0, roadmap.1, consolidate-test-qa, …). A naive "every closed bead needs a
run" rule yields 24 false positives and the audit never goes green. So scope by
a bounded window + an explicit, file-based bypass:

**In-scope set** = closed beads that are BOTH:
1. **Recent**: inside the window (`--bead` → just that bead; `--last N` →
   N most-recent closed; `--since` → closed on/after the date). Default window
   intentionally small so the audit only polices the dogfood-habit era, never
   the pre-habit backlog.
2. **Dev-workflow beads**: NOT in the bypass allowlist (below). A bead is
   presumed dev-workflow (run+gates expected) unless explicitly bypassed —
   "presume expected" is the safe default so silent omissions surface.

**Bypass mechanism (item f — explicit + auditable):** a committed allowlist
file `scripts/dogfood-completeness-allow.txt` (precedent:
`scripts/docs-reality-allow.txt`), one `<bead-id>  # reason` per line (`#`
comments + blank lines ignored). A bead listed here is REPORTED as
`bypass: <bead> — <reason>` (so exceptions stay visible and auditable) but does
NOT cause a non-zero exit. This is the documented path for legit exceptions:
data-backfill / process / doc-only beads with no run (e.g. nm6 gate-backfill,
the deferred 8b7/9ey, the pre-habit infra beads if they ever fall in-window).
Justification for a file over a label: the bypass set is small, needs a written
reason, must be reviewable in a diff, and `bd` labels are not a natural fit for
"this bead is exempt from a tooling check". (Reviewer note: a `no-dogfood-run`
bd label is the plausible alternative — see disagreements.)

**"Gated run" definition (check b):** an in-scope run is "gated" iff its bead
carries a `phase:*` dev-workflow label OR it is not flagged gate-exempt in the
allowlist (a second optional column / a separate `# no-gate` marker). Default:
an in-scope run is expected to have ≥1 gate. Pure doc/process beads that ran but
were Tier-3-single-seat still produce ONE GateAttempt, so they are NOT
gate-exempt by default.

### The checks (each → PASS/FAIL + the ids it reports)
For the in-scope set:

- **(a) run-ref present** — for each in-scope bead, assert
  `refs/etude/runs/etude-<id>` exists (`git rev-parse --verify --quiet`).
  FAIL → `missing run: etude-<id> (no refs/etude/runs/etude-<id>)`.
- **(b) gated run has gate records** — for each in-scope gated run, read
  `git cat-file -p <ref>:manifest.json` and assert `len(gates) > 0` (the
  manifest-blob read both existing scripts use; equivalent to
  `etude run show <bead> | grep -c gate`). FAIL →
  `gateless run: etude-<id> (manifest.gates is empty)`.
- **(c) cadence retro present / not overdue** — count in-scope closed beads
  since the most recent `trigger=cadence-retro` retro (read each
  `refs/etude/retros/*` manifest's `refs.trigger` + `refs.subject_run.*`); the
  standing rule is one cadence retro per 3 closed tickets. FAIL when
  `closed_since_last_cadence_retro >= 3` with no covering cadence retro →
  `cadence retro overdue: N in-scope beads closed since <last-retro-id> (rule: every 3)`.
  Also flag an in-scope cohort bead absent from every cadence retro's
  `subject_run` set → `uncovered by any cadence retro: etude-<id>`.
- **(d) refs pushed (no local-only)** — for every `refs/etude/{runs,retros}/*`,
  compare the local tip (`git for-each-ref`) to origin (`git ls-remote origin
  'refs/etude/*'`); any local ref absent from origin, or whose origin sha differs
  → FAIL `unpushed ref: <refname> (local <sha>, origin <missing|sha>)`. (Verified:
  85 local == 85 origin today, so this is a real, currently-green check.)
- **(e) docs-reality / reconcile where docs changed** — if the audited window's
  commits or the working tree touched docs (`git diff --name-only` +
  `git log --name-only` over the window, matching `README.md|docs/`), run
  `make docs-check` and `make docs-reality`; non-zero → FAIL
  `docs drift: make docs-check/docs-reality failed for doc-touching window`.
  (In `--bead` mode this scopes to that bead's commit.)
- **(f) bypasses reported** — always print the resolved allowlist entries as
  `bypass: <bead> — <reason>` so exceptions are auditable; never affects exit.

**In-scope for THIS bead:** a, b, c, d, e + f. All are mechanically detectable
post-hoc from refs/manifests/git. Nothing deferred — but note (c)'s "overdue"
heuristic is necessarily approximate (it counts closed-in-window beads vs the
every-3 rule; it cannot know an inline-fix retro that produced no artifact), so
it is documented as a heuristic flag, not a hard correctness claim.

### Exit codes + output
- `exit 0` = complete (every check PASS; bypasses are fine).
- `exit 1` = one or more gaps (the standard "audit found gaps" code 8hq.1 keys on).
- `exit 2` = usage / environment error (bad flags, build failure, no closed
  beads) — distinct from a real gap, so the gate can tell "broken" from "gaps".
Text output (default): a per-check section, each gap as
`  - <category>: <bead/run/ref id> — <what's missing>`, then a summary line
`audit: <G> gap(s) across <C> in-scope bead(s); <B> bypass(es).` (OK summary on
0 gaps). `--json` emits the same data machine-readably for the gate.

### Tests (fixture-based, per acceptance "focused tests or fixture-based checks")
A **fixture-based bash test** `scripts/dogfood-completeness-audit_test.sh`
(driven from a new `make` recipe or invoked directly), following the runbook B3
rule "ref-mutating / state tests run in a throwaway repo":
1. Create a throwaway git repo in a `mktemp -d` (trap-cleaned), give it an
   `origin` (a bare repo in the same tmp dir) so the ls-remote push check is real.
2. Seed a COMPLETE fixture: 2-3 fake closed beads (a stub `bd` shim on PATH, or
   pre-seeded `bd` data) each with a `refs/etude/runs/etude-<id>` manifest
   carrying ≥1 gate, a cadence retro ref covering them, all pushed to the bare
   origin, no doc drift → assert the audit prints OK and `exit 0`.
3. Mutate to seed each gap class one at a time and assert the matching finding +
   `exit 1`: delete a run ref (a); empty a manifest's gates (b); add a 3rd closed
   bead with no covering cadence retro (c); create a local-only ref not pushed to
   origin (d); touch a doc to force docs-check/reality failure (e).
4. Assert an allowlisted bead with no run is reported as `bypass:` and does NOT
   flip the exit (f).
Use the same `set -euo pipefail` + array-of-findings assertions as the script.
The `bd` dependency is the only awkward part: the test stubs `bd` via a tiny
shim script on `PATH` that returns canned `bd list --status closed --json`
output — keeping the test hermetic and not touching the real bead store.
(Reviewer note: if any check's logic proves too gnarly for bash to assert
cleanly, the parsing helper could move to a small Go test instead — see
disagreements.)

